<h6>
The simple rule for writing small number is to precisely count
the number of digit(s) after decimal point (.) e.g.
</h6>

<p>
5 tenths = 0.5 (<b>1 digit</b>)
<br>
5 hundredths = 0.05 (<b>2 digits</b>)
<br>
5 thousandths = 0.005 (<b>3 digits</b>)
<br>
5 ten thousandths = 0.0005 (<b>4 digits</b>)
<br>
5 hundred thousandths = 0.00005 (<b>5 digits</b>)
<br>
5 thousand thousandths or 5 millionths = 0.000005 (<b>6 digits</b>)
<br>
<b>Example 1</b>
<br>
Write the following as decimal fractions; 
<br>
(i) 15 thousandths
<br>
(ii) 465/100000
<br> 
(iii) 150 millionths
<br> 
(iv) 200/10000
<br>
<b>Solution</b>
<br>
(i)	15 thousandths = 15 x 1 thousandths = 15 x 0.001 =><b> 0.015</b>
<br>
(ii)	456/100000 = <b>0.00465</b>
<br>
(iii)	150 millionths = 150 x 1 millionths = 150 x 0.000001 = 0.000150 =><b> 0.00015</b>
<br>
(iv)	200/10000 = 0.0200 => <b>0.02</b>
<br>
<h6>
<b>
Note: In a decimal fraction it is not compulsory to write zero (0) after the last non-zero digit.
</b>
</h6>
</p>
